SIMPLE: hectic
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hectic
<hw>Hec"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>hectique</ets>, Gr. <?/ habitual, consumptive, fr. <?/ habit, a
habit of body or mind, fr. <?/ to have; akin to Skr. <ets>sah</ets> to
overpower, endure; cf. AS. <ets>sige</ets>, <ets>sigor</ets>, victory,
G. <ets>sieg</ets>, Goth. <ets>sigis</ets>. Cf. <er>Scheme</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Habitual; constitutional; pertaining especially to slow
waste of animal tissue, as in consumption; <as>as, a <ex>hectic</ex>
type in disease; a <ex>hectic</ex> flush.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In a hectic condition; having hectic fever;
consumptive; <as>as, a <ex>hectic</ex> patient</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hectic fever</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a fever of
irritation and debility, occurring usually at a advanced stage of
exhausting disease, as a in pulmonary consumption.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hectic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hectic
<hw>Hec"tic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld>
<def>Hectic fever.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A hectic flush.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is no living hue, but a strange <qex>hectic</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

